A safety plan should always be created by the person who will be using it. A good safety plan includes these things:
1. Warning Signs
2. Internal Coping Strategies
3. People and Places that Provide Distraction
4. People to Ask for Help
5. Professionals or Agencies to Contact During Crisis
6. Ways to Make the Environment Safe

For more information, check out this video: #IChooseToday

Link to the Stanley & Brown Video ‚Äì found here:

post_text:
September is Suicide Prevention
Awareness Month. We know
that mental illness and suicide
need more attention than a one month campaign.
That‚Äôs why we‚Äôve joined the #IChooseToday
movement. We‚Äôre working with
The Kansas Prevention
Collaborative to share tools to
help us take care of our own
mental health and be supportive
of others all year long. Stay
tuned to learn how to make a
safety plan, connect with
supportive people, and create a
safe living space through safe
storage practices. Will you join
the movement? #IChooseToday
If you or someone you know is
in crisis, call the National Suicide
Prevention Lifeline at 1-800-
273-8255 or chat with the
Lifeline online.

https://knowmoreks.org/i-choose-today/

shared_text:
Kearny County Historical Society Museum
May 15 at 10:40 AM ¬∑

As a result of the school reorganization law of 1945, several rural schools consolidated with Deerfield Grade School. With added students and overcrowded conditions, Deerfield High School District No. 3 voted to build a new high school. Forty-six students and faculty moved into the $330,000 building on Feb. 7, 1950. Even then, the grade school was still too crowded so the 7th and 8th grades were moved into the high school building. The lower grades occupied the old grade school and high school buildings until 1957 when a $316,000 grade school building was erected to house the kindergarten and eight grades. The all-purpose hall in the new building was dedicated in memory of Rex Miller who was a popular member of the Deerfield community and a member of the school board at the time of his untimely death.

With added students and overcrowded conditions, Deerfield High School District No. 3 voted to build a new high school. Forty-six students and faculty moved into the $330,000 building on Feb. 7, 1950. Even then, the grade school was still too crowded so the 7th and 8th grades were moved into the high school building. The lower grades occupied the old grade school and high school buildings until 1957 when a $316,000 grade school building was erected to house the kindergarten and eight grades. The all-purpose hall in the new building was dedicated in memory of Rex Miller who was a popular member of the Deerfield community and a member of the school board at the time of his untimely death.

shared_text:
Kearny County Historical Society Museum
May 8 at 9:32 AM ¬∑

Deerfield's first brick school house was constructed during the years 1910 to 1912 and cost approximately $12,000. During the 1912-1913 school year, grade school students occupied the two lower rooms of the building while 8th graders, freshmen and sophomores were taught in the upper room. Some of the courses taught in the upper room included Latin, Ancient and Medieval History and Progressive English. By the end of the 1914-1915 school year, Deerfield had become a fully accredited three-year high school.

shared_text:
Kearny County Historical Society Museum
May 6 at 9:02 AM ¬∑

This white frame building was the first schoolhouse erected in Deerfield. It was large enough to be divided into two rooms when needed. Completed in 1886, the school opened in October that year with Sallie Eastham as the teacher. When a new brick school building was completed in 1912, this building was sold to the Baptists and moved two blocks south of the school grounds where it served as a church. Later it was used for the first grade classroom, then as an industrial arts class room for the high school and finally as a community building and grange hall.

Attention any sophomores, juniors, or seniors who are interested in taking dual credit classes or starting at #GCCC with us next year. Take advantage of your days off school and come in to take the free Accuplacer placement assessment!

Students who do not have ACT scores or would like to test into a higher math, English, and/ or reading class are able to come in Thursday at 3 p.m. or Friday at 8:30 a.m. to complete the assessment test.

If you have any questions or would like to set up an appointment to to take the Accuplacer, contact our Assessment Center at 620-276-9654. #busternation #gcccadmissions #fromhere

post_text:
Employee Spotlight of the Month: Ana Rojas

As our Spanish-speaking enrollment has risen this year, Ana has met the challenge of being the sole ESOL para for middle and high school head on. She has worked hard to make sure our new students have all the resources and support they need, and that their transition into their new school and new homes is a comfortable one.
During this time she has bounced from classroom to classroom without a break (because she also covers lunch duty and has her own Spartan Council). She has also established meaningful relationships with the increasing number of students she works with, and she‚Äôs done it all with a positive attitude and smile on her face.
Ana, thank you for your dedication and hard work. And congratulations for being selected as the inaugural Employee Spotlight!
